<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-graphing-inequalities-in-two-unknowns" original="section-solving-inequalities-graphically.ptx" license="CC-BY-4.0">
  <title>Graphing Inequalities in Two Unknowns</title>

  <!-- Content summary: - Graph on the Cartesian plane inequalities like 2x + y < 5 (draw the line, use a test point), - Shade the region that statisfies - Compound inequalities, like x - y > 5, 2x < 12, shade region - Use digital resources to represent linear inequalities (STACK exercise etc) -->

  <objectives>
 Represent linear inequalities in two unknowns graphically
  </objectives>

  <!-- Add <insight> here -->

  <!-- BEGIN BORROWED CONTENT -->

<!-- Borrowed from PREALG fs-id1167834431130: Graph Linear Inequalities in Two Variables -->
  
  <p>Now that we know what the graph of a linear inequality looks like and how it relates to a boundary equation we can use this knowledge to graph a given linear inequality.</p>
  
  <example xml:id="PREALG-TTisvXh9gm" original="PREALG/modules/m81372/index.cnxml" license="CC-BY-4.0">
      <statement>
        <p>Graph the linear inequality <m>y \ge \frac{3}{4}x-2.</m>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <image xml:id="PREALG-Hq1fQbWASw" original="PREALG/modules/m81372/index.cnxml" license="CC-BY-4.0" source="PREALG/CNX_IntAlg_Figure_03_04_018a_img_new.jpg" width="80%">
          <description>
                       Step 1 is to Identify and graph the boundary line. If the inequality is less than or equal or greater than or equal, the boundary line is solid. If the inequality is less than or greater than, the boundary line is dashed. In this example the inequality sign is greater than or equal, so we draw a solid line. Replace the inequality sign with an equal sign to find the boundary line. Graph the boundary line y = 3 divided by 4 times x minus 2. The figure then shows the graph of a straight line on the x y-coordinate plane. The x and y-axes run from negative 12 to 12. The line goes through the points (0, negative 2), (4, 1), and (8, 4).
                   </description>
        </image>
        <image xml:id="PREALG-fdt1aEA8o3" original="PREALG/modules/m81372/index.cnxml" license="CC-BY-4.0" source="PREALG/CNX_IntAlg_Figure_03_04_018b_img_new.jpg" width="80%">
          <description>
                       Step 2 is to test a point that is not on the boundary line. Is it a solution of the inequality? We will test (0, 0). At (0, 0) is y greater than or equal to 3 divided by 4 times x minus 2? Is 0 greater than or equal to 3 divided by 4 times 0 minus 2? 0 is greater than or equal to negative 2 so (0, 0) is a solution.
                   </description>
        </image>
        <image xml:id="PREALG-3MR1d9pnEU" original="PREALG/modules/m81372/index.cnxml" license="CC-BY-4.0" source="PREALG/CNX_IntAlg_Figure_03_04_018c_img_new.jpg" width="80%">
          <description>
                       Step 3 is to shade in one side of the boundary line. If the test point is a solution, shade in the side that includes the point. If the test point is not a solution, shade in the opposite side. The test point (0, 0), is a solution to y greater than or equal to 3 divided by 4 times x minus 2. So we shade in the side that contains (0, 0). The figure then shows the graph of a straight line on the x y-coordinate plane. The x and y-axes run from negative 12 to 12. The line goes through the points (0, negative 2), (4, 1), and (8, 4). The top left half of the coordinate plane is shaded to indicate that this is where the solution set is located.
                   </description>
        </image>
      </solution>
    </example>
  
  <p>The steps we take to graph a linear inequality are summarized here.</p>
  
  <insight xml:id="PREALG-FhfdQJUP94" original="PREALG/modules/m81372/index.cnxml" license="CC-BY-4.0">
      <title>Graph a linear inequality in two variables.</title>
      <ol>
        <li>Identify and graph the boundary line. If the inequality is ≤or≥, the boundary line is solid. If the inequality is <or>, the boundary line is dashed.</or>
          <li>Test a point that is not on the boundary line. Is it a solution of the inequality?</li>
          <li>Shade in one side of the boundary line. If the test point is a solution, shade in the side that includes the point. If the test point is not a solution, shade in the opposite side.</li>
        </li>
      </ol>
      <example xml:id="PREALG-9Foke0cf8f" original="PREALG/modules/m81372/index.cnxml" license="CC-BY-4.0">
        <statement>
          <p>Graph the linear inequality <m>x-2y  5.</m>
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>First, we graph the boundary line <m>x-2y=5.</m> The inequality is <m>  </m> so we draw a dashed line.</p>
          <p/>
          <p>Then, we test a point. We’ll use <m>(0,0)</m> again because it is easy to evaluate and it is not on the boundary line.</p>
          <p>Is <m>(0,0)</m> a solution of <m>x-2y  5?</m>
          </p>
          <p/>
          <p>The point <m>(0,0)</m> is a solution of <m>x-2y  5,</m> so we shade in that side of the boundary line.</p>
          <p/>
          <p>All points in the shaded region, but not those on the boundary line, represent the solutions to <m>x-2y  5.</m>
          </p>
        </solution>
      </example>
      <p>What if the boundary line goes through the origin? Then, we won’t be able to use <m>(0,0)</m> as a test point. No problem—we’ll just choose some other point that is not on the boundary line.</p>
      <example xml:id="PREALG-rLdek7hktp" original="PREALG/modules/m81372/index.cnxml" license="CC-BY-4.0">
        <statement>
          <p>Graph the linear inequality: <m>y \le \text{ ​ }-4x.</m>
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>First, we graph the boundary line <m>y=−4x.</m> It is in slope–intercept form, with <m>m=−4</m> and <m>b=0.</m> The inequality is <m> \le </m> so we draw a solid line.</p>
          <p/>
          <p>Now we need a test point. We can see that the point <m>(1,0)</m> is not on the boundary line.</p>
          <p>Is <m>(1,0)</m> a solution of <m>y \le −4x?</m>
          </p>
          <p/>
          <p>The point <m>(1,0)</m> is not a solution to <m>y \le \text{ ​ }-4x,</m> so we shade in the opposite side of the boundary line.</p>
          <p/>
          <p>All points in the shaded region and on the boundary line represent the solutions to <m>y \le \text{ ​ }-4x.</m>
          </p>
        </solution>
      </example>
      <p>Some linear inequalities have only one variable. They may have an <em>x</em> but no <m>y</m>, or a <em>y</em> but no <em>x</em>. In these cases, the boundary line will be either a vertical or a horizontal line.</p>
      <p>Recall that:</p>
      <p>
        <md>
          <mrow>x=a  \text{ vertical line }</mrow>
          <mrow>y=b  \text{ horizontal line }</mrow>
        </md>
      </p>
      <example xml:id="PREALG-mfUaw2o0Wt" original="PREALG/modules/m81372/index.cnxml" license="CC-BY-4.0">
        <statement>
          <p>Graph the linear inequality: <m>y  3.</m>
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>First, we graph the boundary line <m>y=3.</m> It is a horizontal line. The inequality is <m>  </m> so we draw a dashed line.</p>
          <p>We test the point <m>(0,0).</m>
          </p>
          <p>
            <md>
              <mrow>y gt; 3</mrow>
              <mrow>0\cancel{ gt; }3</mrow>
            </md>
          </p>
          <p>So, <m>(0,0)</m> is not a solution to <m>y  3.</m>
          </p>
          <p>So we shade the side that does not include <m>(0,0)</m> as shown in this graph.</p>
          <p/>
          <p>All points in the shaded region, but not those on the boundary line, represent the solutions to <m>y  3.</m>
          </p>
        </solution>
      </example>
      </insight>
  
  <convention>
      <p>This section <xref ref="sec-graphing-inequalities-in-two-unknowns" text="title"/> is adapted from "<url href="https://github.com/openstax/osbooks-prealgebra-bundle/tree/7fcdabf0364f3b308c0190557dfc961b579b374c/modules/m81372/index.cnxml">Graph Linear Inequalities in Two Variables</url>" in Open STAX Elementary Algebra 2e, used under <url href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/deed.en">CC-BY-4.0</url>.</p>
    </convention>

<!-- Borrowed from ORCCA section-inequalities-graphically: Solving Inequalities Graphically -->
  
  <paragraphs xml:id="ORCCA-aBGdQKcEBe" license="CC-BY-4.0"><title>Solving Inequalities Graphically</title></paragraphs>
  
  <p>
        In this text, we have mostly focused on <xref text="custom" provisional="section-solving-multistep-linear-inequalities">solving inequalities algebraically</xref>.
        While we have had some practice solving <xref provisional="subsection-solving-equations-and-inequalities-graphically-using-technology">inequalities graphically</xref> with technology, we want to solidify those skills.
        Solving using graphing is special because the graphing utility we use can do much of the heavy lifting and all that is left is to analyze the graph that is shown to us. So let's let our favorite graphing program make some graphs for us and then we can interpret the results.
      </p>
  
  <figure xml:id="ORCCA-wWCj8tIXeK" license="CC-BY-4.0">
        <caption>Alternative Video Lesson</caption>
        <video youtubeplaylist="PLfPh0EsBc0yJnRjOAWdQp1TjzF7VemI58"/>
      </figure>
  
  <paragraphs xml:id="ORCCA-X5PdrrSn3k" license="CC-BY-4.0"><title>Solving Inequalities Graphically</title></paragraphs>
  
  <idx><h>solving</h><h>inequalities</h><h>graphically</h></idx>
  
  <example xml:id="ORCCA-qu5kDQElEU" license="CC-BY-4.0">
        <sidebyside widths="47% 47%" margins="0%">
          <p>
            Business leaders and professionals around the world concern themselves with money and how to grow their wealth. While a vast majority of people who live in the United States own few or no stocks, the stock market is important to learn about for anyone interested in earning a retirement. Stock owners need to know when to buy or sell their stocks to make a profit and the most essential tool to do so is the ability to read a graph. Let's examine a graph of the actual closing value of Apple (AAPL) stock from June 3, 2019 to August 6, 2019.
          </p>
          <figure xml:id="ORCCA-o9nzOYs2cp" license="CC-BY-4.0">
            <caption>A Graph of AAPL Stock Data</caption>
            <image>
              <shortdescription/>
                <latex-image>
                    \begin{tikzpicture}
                        \begin{axis}[ xmin=-5, xmax=70, 
                                      ymin=160, ymax=220, 
                                      xtick={10,20,...,60}, minor xtick={-5,0,...,70},
                                      xticklabels={6/10,6/20,6/30,7/10,7/20,7/30},
                                      ytick={10,20,...,210}, minor ytick={-5,0,...,220},
                                      axis y discontinuity=crunch,
                                      axis line style={-{Kite}},
                                      ]
                                      \addplot+[-] coordinates {(3, 173) (4, 180) (5, 183) (6, 185) (7, 190) (10,193) (11,195) (12,194) (13,194) (14,193) (17,194) (18,198) (19,198) (20,199) (21,199) (24,199) (25,196) (26,200) (27,200) (28,198) (31,202) (32,203) (33,204) (35,204) (38,200) (39,201) (40,203) (41,202) (42,203) (45,205) (46,205) (47,203) (48,206) (49,203) (52,207) (53,209) (54,209) (55,207) (56,208) (59,210) (60,209) (61,213) (62,208) (63,204) (66,193) (67,197)};
                                      \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(3, 173) (4, 180) (5, 183) (6, 185) (7, 190) (10,193) (11,195) (12,194) (13,194) (14,193) (17,194) (18,198) (19,198) (20,199) (21,199) (24,199) (25,196) (26,200) (27,200) (28,198) (31,202) (32,203) (33,204) (35,204) (38,200) (39,201) (40,203) (41,202) (42,203) (45,205) (46,205) (47,203) (48,206) (49,203) (52,207) (53,209) (54,209) (55,207) (56,208) (59,210) (60,209) (61,213) (62,208) (63,204) (66,193) (67,197)};
                                      \addplot[soliddot,color=secondcolor] coordinates {(6, 185)} node[right]{$(6,185)$};
                        \end{axis}
                    \end{tikzpicture}
                    
                </latex-image>
            </image>
          </figure>
        </sidebyside>
        <p>
          If a person bought the stock on June 6, when the stock was valued at <m>\$185</m> per share, and they wanted at least a <m>\$20</m> per share profit, during what days could they have sold that stock?
        </p>
        <sidebyside widths="47% 47%" margins="0%">
          <p>
            If we want a <m>\$20</m> per share profit, then we should be interested in stock prices of <m>\$205</m> or more. Let's draw a line at <m>y=205</m>, representing the price of <m>\$205</m>, and find any days when the stock was on or above that line. According to the graph, there are several dates in question in starting in late July. Let's zoom in on those dates to read our solutions better.
          </p>
          <figure xml:id="ORCCA-GRUD4i2WGI" license="CC-BY-4.0">
            <caption>A Graph of AAPL Stock Data with <m>y=205</m></caption>
              <image>
              <shortdescription/>
                <latex-image>
                    \begin{tikzpicture}
                        \begin{axis}[ xmin=-5, xmax=70, 
                                      ymin=160, ymax=220, 
                                      xtick={10,20,...,60}, minor xtick={-5,0,...,70},
                                      xticklabels={6/10,6/20,6/30,7/10,7/20,7/30},
                                      ytick={10,20,...,210}, minor ytick={-5,0,...,220},
                                      axis y discontinuity=crunch,
                                      axis line style={-{Kite}},
                                      ]
                                      \addplot+[-] coordinates {(3, 173) (4, 180) (5, 183) (6, 185) (7, 190) (10,193) (11,195) (12,194) (13,194) (14,193) (17,194) (18,198) (19,198) (20,199) (21,199) (24,199) (25,196) (26,200) (27,200) (28,198) (31,202) (32,203) (33,204) (35,204) (38,200) (39,201) (40,203) (41,202) (42,203) (45,205) (46,205) (47,203) (48,206) (49,203) (52,207) (53,209) (54,209) (55,207) (56,208) (59,210) (60,209) (61,213) (62,208) (63,204) (66,193) (67,197)};
                                      \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(3, 173) (4, 180) (5, 183) (6, 185) (7, 190) (10,193) (11,195) (12,194) (13,194) (14,193) (17,194) (18,198) (19,198) (20,199) (21,199) (24,199) (25,196) (26,200) (27,200) (28,198) (31,202) (32,203) (33,204) (35,204) (38,200) (39,201) (40,203) (41,202) (42,203) (45,205) (46,205) (47,203) (48,206) (49,203) (52,207) (53,209) (54,209) (55,207) (56,208) (59,210) (60,209) (61,213) (62,208) (63,204) (66,193) (67,197)};
                                      \addplot[soliddot,color=secondcolor] coordinates {(6, 185)} node[right]{$(6,185)$};
                                      \addplot+[firstcurve,domain=-5:70] {205} node[above,pos=0.2]{$y=205$};
                                      \addplot[soliddot,color=thirdcolor] coordinates {(45,205) (46,205) (48,206) (52,207) (53,209) (54,209) (55,207) (56,208) (59,210) (60,209) (61,213) (62,208)};
                        \end{axis}
                    \end{tikzpicture}
                    
                </latex-image>
            </image>
          </figure>
        </sidebyside>
        <sidebyside widths="47% 47%" margins="0%">
          <p>
            With a zoomed-in and rescaled graph, we can clearly see the dates that would have resulted in a <m>\$20</m> per share profit. Those dates were July 15, 16, 18, 22, 23, 24, 25, 26, 29, 30, 31, and August 1. Keep in mind that the stock market is closed on weekends and holidays, so we are only counting the solid dots as our solutions.
          </p>
          <figure xml:id="ORCCA-Z7XJojH8Xp" license="CC-BY-4.0">
            <caption>A Zoomed-In Graph of AAPL Stock Data with <m>y=205</m></caption>
              <image>
              <shortdescription/>
                <latex-image>
                    \begin{tikzpicture}
                        \begin{axis}[ xmin=40, xmax=65, 
                                      ymin=200, ymax=215, 
                                      xtick={45,50,...,60}, minor xtick={40,41,...,65},
                                      xticklabels={7/15,7/20,7/25,7/30},
                                      ytick={201,202,...,214}, minor ytick={200,201,...,215},
                                      axis y discontinuity=crunch,
                                      axis line style={-{Kite}},
                                      ]
                                      \addplot+[-] coordinates {(40,203) (41,202) (42,203) (45,205) (46,205) (47,203) (48,206) (49,203) (52,207) (53,209) (54,209) (55,207) (56,208) (59,210) (60,209) (61,213) (62,208) (63,204) (66,193) (67,197)};
                                      \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(40,203) (41,202) (42,203) (45,205) (46,205) (47,203) (48,206) (49,203) (52,207) (53,209) (54,209) (55,207) (56,208) (59,210) (60,209) (61,213) (62,208) (63,204) (66,193) (67,197)};
                                      \addplot[soliddot,color=secondcolor] coordinates {(6, 185)} node[right]{$(6,185)$};
                                      \addplot+[firstcurve,domain=40:70] {205} node[above,pos=0.6]{$y=205$};
                                      \addplot[soliddot,color=thirdcolor] coordinates {(45,205) (46,205) (48,206) (52,207) (53,209) (54,209) (55,207) (56,208) (59,210) (60,209) (61,213) (62,208)};
                        \end{axis}
                    \end{tikzpicture}
                    
                </latex-image>
            </image>
          </figure>
        </sidebyside>
      </example>
  
  <p>
        Let's turn to an example involving a linear equation.
      </p>
  
  <example xml:id="ORCCA-vvLMKtGwIg" license="CC-BY-4.0">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Solve the inequality <m>3x-2\lt7</m> graphically.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <sidebyside widths="47% 47%" margins="0%">
            <p>
              To solve any inequality (or equation) graphically,
              we first take each side of the equation and graph <m>y=\text{"left hand side"}</m>
              and <m>y=\text{"right hand side"}</m>.
              In this case, that would be <m>y=3x-2</m> and <m>y=7</m>.
              Now we can see that the graphs of <m>y=3x-2</m> and <m>y=7</m> intersect at the point <m>(3,7)</m>.
            </p>
            <figure xml:id="ORCCA-AB5jxzS3zk" license="CC-BY-4.0">
              <caption>A Graph of Both <m>y=3x-2</m> and <m>y=7</m></caption>
                <image>
                <shortdescription/>
                  <latex-image>
                      \begin{tikzpicture}
                          \begin{axis}[ xmin=-2, xmax=5,
                                        ymin=-10, ymax=14,
                                        xtick={-1,0,...,4}, minor xtick={-2,-1,...,5},
                                        ytick={-8,-6,...,12}, minor ytick={-10,-9,...,14},
                                        ]
                                        \addplot+[domain=-2:5] {3*x-2} node[above,pos=0.5,sloped]{$y=3x-2$};
                                        \addplot+[domain=-2:5] {7} node[above,pos=0.5]{$y=7$};
                                        \addplot[soliddot,color=fourthcolor] coordinates {(3,7)} node[below right]{$(3,7)$};
                          \end{axis}
                      \end{tikzpicture}
                      
                  </latex-image>
              </image>
            </figure>
          </sidebyside>
          <sidebyside widths="47% 47%" margins="0%">
            <p>
              Since we are trying to solve the inequality <m>3x-2\lt7</m>,
              we need to examine the graph for where (what <m>x</m>-values)
              the graph of <m>y=3x-2</m> is below the graph of <m>y=7</m>.
              This happens for <m>x</m>-values less than <m>3</m>.
              So we would say that the solution set to <m>3x-2\lt7</m> is <m>(-\infty,3)</m>.
              It is review to solve the inequality algebraically to verify our result.
            </p>
            <figure xml:id="ORCCA-FX7daQEkSk" license="CC-BY-4.0">
              <caption>A Graph of Both <m>y=3x-2</m> and <m>y=7</m></caption>
                <image>
                <shortdescription/>
                  <latex-image>
                      \begin{tikzpicture}
                          \begin{axis}[ xmin=-2, xmax=5,
                                        ymin=-10, ymax=14,
                                        xtick={-1,0,...,4}, minor xtick={-2,-1,...,5},
                                        ytick={-8,-6,...,12}, minor ytick={-10,-9,...,14},
                                        ]
                                        \addplot+[domain=-2:5] {3*x-2} node[above,pos=0.5,sloped]{$y=3x-2$};
                                        \addplot+[domain=-2:5] {7} node[above,pos=0.5]{$y=7$};
                                        \addplot[hollowdot,draw=fourthcolor] coordinates {(3,7)} node[below right]{$(3,7)$};
                                        \addplot[highlightcurve,domain=-2:3] {3*x-2};
                                        \addplot[guideline] coordinates {(3,7) (3,0)};
                                        \addplot[infiniteopeninterval] coordinates {(-2,0) (3,0)};
                          \end{axis}
                      \end{tikzpicture}
                      
                  </latex-image>
              </image>
            </figure>
          </sidebyside>
        </solution>
      </example>
  
  <paragraphs xml:id="ORCCA-j4hCTt7ku0" license="CC-BY-4.0"><title>Solving Absolute Value and Quadratic Inequalities Graphically</title></paragraphs>
  
  <p>
        Recall in <xref provisional="section-absolute-value-equations">Section</xref>
        that we learned that graphs of absolute value function are in general shaped like <q>V</q>s.
        We can now solve some absolute value inequalities graphically.
      </p>
  
  <example xml:id="ORCCA-vz1Y6JXnHp" license="CC-BY-4.0">
        <sidebyside widths="47% 47%" margins="0%">
        <p>
          Graphically solving the inequality
          <m>\abs{2x-1} \le 5</m> means looking for the <m>x</m>-values where the graph of <m>y=\abs{2x-1}</m> is below
          (or touching)
          the line <m>y=5</m>.
          On the graph the highlighted region of
          <m>y=\abs{2x-1}</m> is the portion that is below the line <m>y=5</m>,
          and the <m>x</m>-values in that region are <m>[-2,3]</m>.
        </p>
        <figure xml:id="ORCCA-wiBhGFAzmv" license="CC-BY-4.0">
          <caption><m>y=\abs{2x-1}</m> and <m>y=5</m></caption>
          <image>
            <shortdescription>a Cartesian graph with the graphs of y=abs(2x-1) and y=5;y=abs(2x-1) has its vertex at (1/2,0) with a slope of 2 on the right and -2 on the left;y=5 is a horizontal line;the graphs cross at the points (-2,5) and (3,5);the V-shaped graph is highlighted below the line y=5 with open circles at the intersection points</shortdescription>
              <latex-image>
                  \begin{tikzpicture}
                      \begin{axis}[xmin=-7, xmax=7, ymin=-2, ymax=7, xtick={-6,-5,...,6}, ytick={-1,0,...,6}]
                      \addplot[firstcurve] coordinates {(-3,7) (0.5,0) (4,7)} node[pos=0.65,below,sloped] {$y=\abs{2x-1}$};
                      \addplot[highlightcurve] coordinates {(-2,5) (0.5,0) (3,5)};
                      \addplot[secondcurve, domain=-7:7] {5} node[pos=0.2, above]{$y=5$};
                      \addplot[soliddot, color=fourthcolor] coordinates {(3,5)};
                      \addplot[soliddot, color=fourthcolor] coordinates {(-2, 5)};
                      \addplot[guideline] coordinates {(-2,5) (-2,0)};
                      \addplot[guideline] coordinates {(3,5) (3,0)};
                      \addplot[closedinterval] coordinates {(-2,0) (3,0)};
                      \end{axis}
                  \end{tikzpicture}
                  
              </latex-image>
          </image>
        </figure>
      </sidebyside>
      </example>
  
  <example xml:id="ORCCA-3YwCPHoQVc" license="CC-BY-4.0">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Solve the inequality <m>\abs{\frac{2}{3}x+1} \lt 3</m> graphically.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            To solve the inequality <m>\abs{\frac{2}{3}x+1} \lt 3</m>,
            we will start by making a graph with both <m>y=\abs{\frac{2}{3}x+1}</m> and <m>y=3</m>.
          </p>
          <sidebyside widths="47% 47%" margins="0%">
            <p>
              The portion of the graph of
              <m>y=\abs{\frac{2}{3}x+1}</m> that is below <m>y=3</m> is highlighted and the <m>x</m>-values of that highlighted region are trapped between <m>-6</m> and <m>3</m>:
              <m>-6 \lt x \lt 3</m>.
              That means that the solution set is <m>(-6,3)</m>.
              Note that we shouldn't include the endpoints of the interval because at those values,
              the two graphs are <em>equal</em>
              whereas the original inequality was only
              <em>less than</em> and not equal.
            </p>
            <figure xml:id="ORCCA-1Sy3oyTbdS" license="CC-BY-4.0">
              <caption><m>y=\abs{\frac{2}{3}x+1}</m> and <m>y=3</m></caption>
              <image>
                <shortdescription>a Cartesian graph with the graphs of y=abs(2/3x+1) and y=3;y=abs(2/3x+1) has its vertex at (-3/2,0) with a slope of 2/3 on the right and -2/3 on the left;y=3 is a horizontal line;the graphs cross at the points (-6,3) and (3,3);the V-shaped graph is highlighted below the line y=3 with open circles at the intersection points</shortdescription>
              <latex-image>
                  \begin{tikzpicture}
                      \begin{axis}[xmin=-10, xmax=7, ymin=-1, ymax=6, xtick={-8,-6,...,6}, ytick={0,1,...,5}, minor xtick={-10,-9,...,7}]
                      \addplot[firstcurve] coordinates {(-10,5.667) (-1.5,0) (7,5.667)} node[pos=0.12,sloped,above] {$y=\abs{\frac{2}{3}x+1}$};
                      \addplot[secondcurve, domain=-10:7] {3} node[pos=0.9, below]{$y=3$};
                      \addplot[highlightcurve, domain=-6:3] coordinates {(-6,3) (-1.5,0) (3,3)};
                      \addplot[hollowdot, draw=fourthcolor] coordinates {(-6,3)};
                      \addplot[hollowdot, draw=fourthcolor] coordinates {(3,3)};
                      \addplot[guideline] coordinates {(-6,3) (-6,0)};
                      \addplot[guideline] coordinates {(3,3) (3,0)};
                      \addplot[openinterval] coordinates {(-6,0) (3,0)};
                      \end{axis}
                  \end{tikzpicture}
                  
              </latex-image>
              </image>
            </figure>
          </sidebyside>
        </solution>
      </example>
  
  <p>
        The last examples had absolute value expressions being
        <em>less than</em> some value.
        We now need to investigate what happens when we have an absolute value expression that is
        <em>greater than</em> a value.
      </p>
  
  <example xml:id="ORCCA-uu2T2S1jWW" license="CC-BY-4.0">
        <p>
          To graphically solve the inequality
          <m>\abs{x-1} \gt 3</m> would mean looking for the <m>x</m>-values where the graph of <m>y=\abs{x-1}</m> is
          <em>above</em> the line <m>y=3</m>.
        </p>
        <sidebyside widths="47% 47%" margins="0%">
          <p>
            On the graph the highlighted region of
            <m>y=\abs{x-1}</m> is the portion that is above the line <m>y=3</m> and the <m>x</m>-values in that region can be represented by <m>(-\infty,-2)\cup(4,\infty)</m>.
          </p>
          <figure xml:id="ORCCA-K4xLiBoxFv" license="CC-BY-4.0">
            <caption><m>y=\abs{x-1}</m> and <m>y=3</m></caption>
            <image>
              <shortdescription>a Cartesian graph with the graphs of y=abs(x-1) and y=3;y=abs(x-1) has its vertex at (1,0) with a slope of 1 on the right and -1 on the left;y=3 is a horizontal line;the graphs cross at the points (-2,3) and (4,3);the V-shaped graph is highlighted above the line y=3 with open circles at the points of intersection</shortdescription>
              <latex-image>
                  \begin{tikzpicture}
                      \begin{axis}[xmin=-7, xmax=7, ymin=-2, ymax=7, ytick={-1,0,...,6}]
                      \addplot[firstcurve] coordinates {(-6,7) (1,0) (7,6)} node[pos=0.17, sloped, above]{$y=\abs{x-1}$};
                      \addplot[secondcurve, domain=-7:7] {3} node[pos=0.2, below]{$y=3$};
                      \addplot[highlightcurve, domain=-5.7:-2] {abs(x-1)};
                      \addplot[highlightcurve, domain=4:6.7] {abs(x-1)};
                      \addplot[hollowdot, draw=fourthcolor] coordinates {(-2,3)};
                      \addplot[hollowdot, draw=fourthcolor] coordinates {(4,3)};
                      \addplot[guideline] coordinates {(-2,3) (-2,0)};
                      \addplot[guideline] coordinates {(4,3) (4,0)};
                      \addplot[infiniteopeninterval] coordinates {(-7,0) (-2,0)};
                      \addplot[openinfiniteinterval] coordinates {(4,0) (7,0)};
                      \end{axis}
                  \end{tikzpicture}
                  
              </latex-image>
            </image>
          </figure>
        </sidebyside>
      </example>
  
  <example xml:id="ORCCA-y7AoF6gV5I" license="CC-BY-4.0">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Solve the inequality <m>\abs{\frac{1}{3}x+2} \ge 6</m> graphically.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            To solve the inequality <m>\abs{\frac{1}{3}x+2} \ge 6</m>,
            we will start by making a graph with both <m>y=\abs{\frac{1}{3}x+2}</m> and <m>y=6</m>.
          </p>
          <sidebyside widths="47% 47%" margins="0%">
            <p>
              The portion of the graph of
              <m>y=\abs{\frac{1}{3}x+2}</m> that is above <m>y=6</m> is highlighted and the <m>x</m>-values of that highlighted region are those below
              (or equal to)
              <m>-24</m> and those above
              (or equal to)
              <m>12</m>:
              <m>x \le -24 \text{ or } x \ge 12</m>.
              That means that the solution set is <m>(-\infty,-24]\cup[12,\infty)</m>.
            </p>
            <figure xml:id="ORCCA-PY8sJDjaYW" license="CC-BY-4.0">
              <caption><m>y=\abs{\frac{1}{3}x+2}</m> and <m>y=3</m></caption>
              <image>
                <shortdescription>a Cartesian graph with the graphs of y=abs(1/3x+2) and y=6;y=abs(1/3x+2) has its vertex at (-6,0) with a slope of 1/3 on the right and -1/3 on the left;y=6 is a horizontal line;the graphs cross at the points (-24,6) and (12,6);the V-shaped graph is highlighted above the line y=6 with solid circles at the points of intersection</shortdescription>
              <latex-image>
                  \begin{tikzpicture}
                      \begin{axis}[xmin=-40, xmax=20, ymin=-2, ymax=10, xtick={-32,-24,...,16}, ytick={-1,0,...,9}, minor xtick={-40,-36,...,20},minor ytick={-2,-1,...,10}]
                      \addplot[firstcurve] coordinates {(-36,10) (-6,0) (20,8.667)}  node[pos=0.36, sloped, below]{$y=\abs{\frac{1}{3}x+2}$};
                      \addplot[secondcurve, domain=-40:20] {6} node[pos=0.45, above]{$y=6$};
                      \addplot[highlightcurve, domain=-34.5:-24] {abs((1/3)*x+2)};
                      \addplot[highlightcurve, domain=12:18.5] {abs((1/3)*x+2)};
                      \addplot[soliddot, color=fourthcolor] coordinates {(-24,6)};
                      \addplot[soliddot, color=fourthcolor] coordinates {(12,6)};
                      \addplot[guideline] coordinates {(-24,6) (-24,0)};
                      \addplot[guideline] coordinates {(12,6) (12,0)};
                      \addplot[infiniteclosedinterval] coordinates {(-40,0) (-24,0)};
                      \addplot[closedinfiniteinterval] coordinates {(12,0) (20,0)};
                      \end{axis}
                  \end{tikzpicture}
                  
              </latex-image>
              </image>
            </figure>
          </sidebyside>
        </solution>
      </example>
  
  <p>
        Solving inequalities with quadratic expressions graphically is very similar to solving absolute value inequalities graphically.
      </p>
  
  <example xml:id="ORCCA-K8X1S7ZVpZ" license="CC-BY-4.0">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Graphically solve the following quadratic inequalities.
            <ol marker="a." cols="2" xml:id="ORCCA-1VyW4zIyfj" license="CC-BY-4.0">
              <li xml:id="ORCCA-ibTTD4HeOO" license="CC-BY-4.0">
                <p>
                  <m>42(x-2)^2-60 \geq 21x-39</m>
                </p>
              </li>
  
              <li xml:id="ORCCA-Kd7yMnSd7N" license="CC-BY-4.0">
                <p>
                  <m>42(x-2)^2-60 \lt 21x-39</m>
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <sidebyside widths="47% 47%" margins="0%">
            <p>
              For both parts of this example, we start by graphing the equations <m>y=42(x-2)^2-60</m> and
              <m>y=21x-39</m> using graphing technology, and determining the points of intersection.
            </p>
  
            <figure xml:id="ORCCA-aQHDhljvTx" license="CC-BY-4.0">
              <caption>Points of intersection for <m>y=42(x-2)^2-60</m> and <m>y=21x-39</m></caption>
              <image width="47%">
                <shortdescription/>
                <latex-image>
                    \begin{tikzpicture}
                        \begin{axis}[ xmin=-1,xmax=5,
                                      ymin=-80,ymax=80,
                                      xtick={1,2,3,4},minor xtick={-1,0,...,5},
                                      ytick={-60,-40,...,60},minor ytick={-80,-60,...,80},
                                      clip=false,
                                      ]
                            \addplot+[domain=.174:3.826] {42*x^2-168*x+108};
                            \addplot+[domain=-1:5] {21*x-39};
                            \addplot[soliddot, color=fourthcolor] coordinates {(1,-18)} node[right]{$(1,-18)$};
                            \addplot[soliddot, color=fifthcolor] coordinates {(3.5,34.5)} node[below right]{$(3.5,34.5)$};
                        \end{axis}
                    \end{tikzpicture}
                    
                </latex-image>
              </image>
            </figure>
          </sidebyside>
  
          <p>
            <ol marker="a." xml:id="ORCCA-VitNm9Fg0l" license="CC-BY-4.0">
              <li xml:id="ORCCA-0KWwrqP7vX" license="CC-BY-4.0">
                <p>
                  To solve <m>42(x-2)^2-60 \ge 21x-39</m>,
                  we need to determine where the <m>y</m>-values of the parabola
                  are higher than (or equal to) those of the line.
                  This region is highlighted in <xref ref="ORCCA-TE4h85l9G7">Figure</xref>.
                </p>
                <sidebyside widths="47% 47%" margins="0%">
                  <p>
                    We can see that <m>42(x-2)^2-60 \ge 21x-39</m> for all values of <m>x</m> where <m>x\le 1</m> or <m>x\ge 3.5</m>.
                    We can write this solution set in <xref text="custom" provisional="definition-interval-notation">interval notation</xref> as
                    <m>(-\infty,1]\cup[3.5,\infty)</m> or in <xref text="custom" provisional="definition-set-builder-notation">set-builder notation</xref> as <m>\{x\mid x\le 1 \text{ or } x\ge 3.5\}</m>.
                  </p>
  
                  <figure xml:id="ORCCA-TE4h85l9G7" license="CC-BY-4.0">
                    <caption>Where <m>42(x-2)^2-60\ge21x-39</m></caption>
                    <image width="47%">
                      <shortdescription/>
                      <latex-image>
                          \begin{tikzpicture}
                              \begin{axis}[ xmin=-1,xmax=5,
                                            ymin=-80,ymax=80,
                                            xtick={1,2,3,4},minor xtick={-1,0,...,5},
                                            ytick={-60,-40,...,60},minor ytick={-80,-60,...,80},
                                            clip=false,
                                            ]
                                  \addplot+[domain=.174:3.826] {42*x^2-168*x+108};
                                  \addplot+[domain=-1:5] {21*x-39};
                                  \addplot[soliddot, color=fourthcolor] coordinates {(1,-18)} node[right]{$(1,-18)$};
                                  \addplot[soliddot, color=fifthcolor] coordinates {(3.5,34.5)} node[below right]{$(3.5,34.5)$};
                                  \addplot+[highlightcurve,domain=.174:1] {42*x^2-168*x+108};
                                  \addplot+[highlightcurve,domain=3.5:3.826] {42*x^2-168*x+108};
                                  \addplot[infiniteclosedinterval,color=fourthcolor] coordinates {(-1,0) (1,0)};
                                  \addplot[closedinfiniteinterval,color=fourthcolor] coordinates {(3.5,0) (5,0)};
                                  \addplot[guideline] coordinates {(1,0) (1,-18)};
                                  \addplot[guideline] coordinates {(3.5,0) (3.5,34.5)};
                              \end{axis}
                          \end{tikzpicture}
                          
                      </latex-image>
                    </image>
                  </figure>
                </sidebyside>
  
              </li>
  
              <li xml:id="ORCCA-kUe7FTnYze" license="CC-BY-4.0">
                <p>
                  To now solve <m>42(x-2)^2-60 \lt 21x-39</m>,
                  we will need to determine where the <m>y</m>-values of the parabola are <em>less</em> than
                  those of the line.
                  This region is highlighted in <xref ref="ORCCA-LmDGqzdBk2">Figure</xref>.
                </p>
                <sidebyside widths="47% 47%" margins="0%">
                  <p>
                    So the solutions to this inequality include all values of <m>x</m> for which <m>1\lt x \lt 3.5</m>.
                    We can write this solution set in <xref text="custom" provisional="definition-interval-notation">interval notation</xref>
                    as <m>(1,3.5)</m>
                    or in <xref text="custom" provisional="definition-set-builder-notation">set-builder notation</xref>
                    as <m>\{x \mid 1 \lt x \lt 3.5\}</m>.
                  </p>
  
                  <figure xml:id="ORCCA-LmDGqzdBk2" license="CC-BY-4.0">
                    <caption>Where <m>42(x-2)^2-60\lt21x-39</m></caption>
                    <image width="47%">
                      <shortdescription/>
                      <latex-image>
                          \begin{tikzpicture}
                              \begin{axis}[ xmin=-1,xmax=5,
                                            ymin=-80,ymax=80,
                                            xtick={1,2,3,4},minor xtick={-1,0,...,5},
                                            ytick={-60,-40,...,60},minor ytick={-80,-60,...,80},
                                            clip=false,
                                            ]
                                  \addplot+[domain=.174:3.826] {42*x^2-168*x+108};
                                  \addplot+[domain=-1:5] {21*x-39};
                                  \addplot[hollowdot, draw=fourthcolor] coordinates {(1,-18)} node[right]{$(1,-18)$};
                                  \addplot[hollowdot, draw=fifthcolor] coordinates {(3.5,34.5)} node[below right]{$(3.5,34.5)$};
                                  \addplot+[highlightcurve,domain=1:3.5] {42*x^2-168*x+108};
                                  \addplot[openinterval,color=fourthcolor] coordinates {(1,0) (3.5,0)};
                                  \addplot[guideline] coordinates {(1,0) (1,-18)};
                                  \addplot[guideline] coordinates {(3.5,0) (3.5,34.5)};
                              \end{axis}
                          \end{tikzpicture}
                          
                      </latex-image>
                    </image>
                  </figure>
                </sidebyside>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </solution>
      </example>
  
  <paragraphs xml:id="ORCCA-hIL1YisTVD" license="CC-BY-4.0"><title>Solving Compound Inequalities Graphically</title></paragraphs>
  
  <example xml:id="ORCCA-QrOjuhKdjO" license="CC-BY-4.0">
        <statement>
          <sidebyside widths="47% 47%" margins="0%">
            <p>
              <xref ref="ORCCA-L3uIDua1vy">Figure</xref>
              shows a graph of <m>y=f(x)</m>.
              Use the graph to solve the inequality <m>2\le f(x) \lt 6</m>.
            </p>
            <figure xml:id="ORCCA-L3uIDua1vy" license="CC-BY-4.0">
              <caption>Graph of <m>y=f(x)</m></caption>
              <image>
                <shortdescription>A Cartesian graph of one line, y=f(x), whose formula is unknown. f passes through (-4,6) and (4,2).</shortdescription>
                <latex-image>
                    \begin{tikzpicture}
                        \begin{axis}[clip=false, ymin=-5, ymax=9, ytick={-4,-2,...,8}, minor ytick={-5,-4,...,9}]
                        \addplot[firstcurve, domain=-7:7] {4-0.5*x} node[above, sloped, pos=0.62]{$y=f(x)$};
                        \end{axis}
                    \end{tikzpicture}
                    
                </latex-image>
              </image>
            </figure>
          </sidebyside>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <sidebyside widths="47% 47%" margins="0%">
            <p>
              To solve the inequality <m>2\le f(x) \lt 6</m> means to find the
              <m>x</m>-values that give function values between <m>2</m> and <m>6</m>,
              not including <m>6</m>.
              We draw the horizontal lines <m>y=2</m> and <m>y=6</m>.
              Then we look for the points of intersection and find their <m>x</m>-values.
              We see that when <m>x</m> is between <m>-4</m> and <m>4</m>,
              not including <m>-4</m>, the inequality will be true.
              We have drawn the interval <m>(-4,4]</m> along the <m>x</m>-axis,
              which is the solution set.
            </p>
            <figure xml:id="ORCCA-ekMm7Acj66" license="CC-BY-4.0">
              <caption>Graph of <m>y=f(x)</m> and the solution set to <m>2\le f(x) \lt 6</m></caption>
              <image width="47%">
                <shortdescription>A Cartesian graph of three lines, y=f(x) whose formulas is unknown, y=2 a solid horizontal line, and y=6, a dashed horizontal line. f passes through (-4,6) and (4,2). Note that the lines intersect at (-4,6) with an open dot, and at (4,2) with a solid dot.</shortdescription>
                <latex-image>
                  \begin{tikzpicture}
                                \begin{axis}[clip=false, 
                                            ymin=-5, ymax=9,
                                            ytick={-4,-2,...,8}, minor ytick={-5,-4,...,9},
                                            ]
                                \addplot+[domain=-7:7] {4-0.5*x} node[above, sloped, pos=0.62] {$y=f(x)$};
                                \addplot[domain=-4:4, highlightcurve] {4-0.5*x};
                                \addplot[closedboundary, color=fifthcolor] {2} node[below, pos=0.1]{$y=2$};
                                \addplot[openboundary, color=fourthcolor] {6} node[below, pos=0.1]{$y=6$};
                                \addplot[hollowdot, draw=fourthcolor] coordinates {(-4,6)};
                                \addplot[soliddot, color=fifthcolor] coordinates {(4,2)};
                                \addplot[guideline,dashed] coordinates {(-4,6) (-4,0)};
                                \addplot[guideline,dashed] coordinates {(4,2) (4,0)};
                                \addplot[openclosedinterval, color=secondcolor] coordinates {(-4,0) (4,0)};
                                \end{axis}
                  \end{tikzpicture}
                </latex-image>
              </image>
            </figure>
          </sidebyside>
        </solution>
      </example>
  
  <example xml:id="ORCCA-QqCVI5t5HW" license="CC-BY-4.0">
        <statement>
          <p>
            <xref ref="ORCCA-DAucIpt6pa">Figure</xref>
            shows a graph of <m>y=g(x)</m>.
            Use the graph to solve the inequality <m>-4\lt g(x) \le 3</m>.
          </p>
          <figure xml:id="ORCCA-DAucIpt6pa" license="CC-BY-4.0">
            <caption>Graph of <m>y=g(x)</m></caption>
            <image width="47%">
              <shortdescription>A Cartesian graph of a cubic curve, y=g(x), whose formula is unknown.</shortdescription>
              <latex-image>
                  \begin{tikzpicture}
                      \begin{axis}[clip=false, xmin=-4, xmax=4, xtick={-3,-2,...,3},
                                  ymin=-7,ymax=5,width=0.47\linewidth]
                      \addplot[firstcurve, domain=-2.405:3.29, smooth] {0.75*(x-3)*(x+1)^2+1} node[right, pos=0.95]{$y=g(x)$};
                      \end{axis}
                  \end{tikzpicture}
                  
              </latex-image>
            </image>
          </figure>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            To solve <m>-4\lt g(x) \le 3</m>,
            we first draw the horizontal lines <m>y=-4</m> and <m>y=3</m>.
            To solve this inequality we notice that there are two pieces of the function <m>g</m> that are trapped between the <m>y</m>-values <m>-4</m> and <m>3</m>.
          </p>
          <p>
            The solution set is the compound inequality <m>(-2.1,0.7)\cup(2.4,3.2]</m>.
          </p>
          <figure xml:id="ORCCA-ZrhaCmaVOj" license="CC-BY-4.0">
            <caption>Graph of <m>y=g(x)</m> and solution set to <m>-4\lt g(x) \le 3</m></caption>
            <image width="47%">
              <shortdescription>A Cartesian graph of the cubic curve y=g(x) whose formula is unknown. There is a dotted line at y=-4 and a solid line at y=3.</shortdescription>
              <latex-image>
                  \begin{tikzpicture}
                              \begin{axis}[clip=false, xmin=-4, xmax=4, xtick={-3,-2,...,3},
                              ymin=-7,ymax=5,width=0.47\linewidth]
                              \addplot+[domain=-2.405:3.29, smooth] {0.75*(x-3)*(x+1)^2+1} node[above, pos=1]{$y=g(x)$};
                              \addplot[openboundary, domain=-4:4, color=fifthcolor] {-4} node[right, pos=1]{$y=-4$};
                              \addplot[closedboundary, domain=-4:4, color=fourthcolor] {3} node[right, pos=1]{$y=3$};
                              \addplot[domain=-2.139:0.704, smooth, highlightcurve] {0.75*(x-3)*(x+1)^2+1};
                              \addplot[domain=2.435:3.155, smooth, highlightcurve] {0.75*(x-3)*(x+1)^2+1};
                              \addplot[hollowdot, draw=fifthcolor] coordinates {(-2.139,-4)};
                              \addplot[hollowdot, draw=fifthcolor] coordinates {(0.704,-4)};
                              \addplot[hollowdot, draw=fifthcolor] coordinates {(2.435,-4)};
                              \addplot[soliddot, color=fourthcolor] coordinates {(3.155,3)};
                              \addplot[guideline,dashed] coordinates {(-2.139,-4) (-2.139,0)};
                              \addplot[guideline,dashed] coordinates {(0.704, -4) (0.704,0)};
                              \addplot[guideline,dashed] coordinates {(2.435,-4) (2.435,0)};
                              \addplot[guideline,dashed] coordinates {(3.155, 3) (3.155,0)};
                              \addplot[openinterval, color=secondcolor] coordinates {(-2.139,0) (0.704,0)};
                              \addplot[openclosedinterval, color=secondcolor] coordinates {(2.435,0) (3.155,0)};
                              \end{axis}
                          \end{tikzpicture}
                          
                      </latex-image>
            </image>
          </figure>
        </solution>
      </example>
  
  <example xml:id="ORCCA-OL4Q6CUVnm" license="CC-BY-4.0">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Phuong is taking the standard climbing route on Mount Hood from Timberline Lodge up the Southside Hogsback to the summit and back down the same way.
            Her altitude can be very closely modeled by an absolute value function since the angle of ascent is nearly constant.
            Let <m>x</m> represent the number of miles walked from Timberline Lodge,
            and let <m>f(x)</m> represent the altitude, in miles,
            after walking for a distance <m>x</m>.
            The altitude can be modeled by <m>f\left(x\right)=2.1-0.3077\cdot\abs{x-3.25}</m>.
            Note that below Timberline Lodge this model fails to be accurate.
            <ol marker="a." xml:id="ORCCA-5ynd2zaNao" license="CC-BY-4.0">
              <li xml:id="ORCCA-iDodivoa0a" license="CC-BY-4.0">
                <p>
                  Solve the equation <m>f(x)=1.1</m> graphically and interpret the results in the context of the problem.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li xml:id="ORCCA-0brG4bAIPO" license="CC-BY-4.0">
                <p>
                  Altitude sickness can occur at or above altitudes <m>1.5</m> miles.
                  Set up and solve an inequality graphically to find out how far Phuong can walk the trail and still be under <m>1.5</m> miles of elevation.
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            <ol marker="a." xml:id="ORCCA-z8zseScGIo" license="CC-BY-4.0">
              <li xml:id="ORCCA-fJDNPaojci" license="CC-BY-4.0">
                <p>
                  First, we substitute the formula for <m>f(x)</m> and simplify the equation.
                  <md>
                    <mrow>f(x)\amp=1.1</mrow>
                    <mrow>2.1-0.3077\cdot\abs{x-3.25} \amp=1.1</mrow>
                    <!-- <mrow>2.1-0.3077\cdot\abs{x-3.25}\subtractright{2.1} \amp= 1.1\subtractright{2.1}</mrow> -->
                    <!-- <mrow>-0.3077\cdot\abs{x-3.25} \amp= -1</mrow> -->
                    <!-- <mrow>\divideunder{-0.3077\cdot\abs{x-3.25}}{-0.3077} \amp= \divideunder{-1}{-0.3077}</mrow> -->
                    <!-- <mrow>\abs{x-3.25} \amp\approx 3.25</mrow> -->
                  </md>
                  At this point, we should make a graph of both <m>y=2.1-0.3077\cdot\abs{x-3.25}</m> and <m>y=1.1</m> and find their intersections.
                </p>
                  <sidebyside widths="47% 47%" margins="0%">
                    <p>
                      Next, we should note that we are looking for the <m>x</m>-values of the intersections.
                      These solutions are <m>0</m> and <m>6.5</m>. According to the model, Phuong will be at <m>1.1</m> miles of elevation after walking about <m>0</m> miles as well as about <m>6.5</m> miles along the trail.
                      This implies that Timberline Lodge is at <m>1.1</m> miles of elevation.
                      In addition,
                      it implies that the entire hike is <m>6.5</m> miles round trip,
                      ending at Timberline Lodge again.
                    </p>
                  <figure xml:id="ORCCA-roIQn1iQfQ" license="CC-BY-4.0">
                    <caption><m>y=f(x)</m> and <m>y=1.1</m></caption>
                    <image>
                      <shortdescription>a Cartesian graph with the graphs of f(x)=2.1-0.3077abs(x-3.25) and y=1.1 and y=1.5;the absolute value is an upside-down V which is highlighted above y=1.1 and below 1.5, with open circles where y=1.5</shortdescription>
                      <latex-image>
                           \begin{tikzpicture}
                              \begin{axis}[ xmin=-1, xmax=8, 
                                            ymin=-.5, ymax=3, 
                                            xtick={1,2,...,7}, 
                                            ytick={0.5,1,...,2.5},
                                            ]
                                \addplot+[firstcurve] coordinates {(-1,0.792) (3.25,2.1) (8,0.6385)} node[pos=0.3, sloped, above]{$y=f(x)$};
                                \addplot+[domain=-1:8] {1.1};
                                \addplot[soliddot,color=thirdcolor] coordinates {(0,1.1)} node[below right]{$(0,1.1)$};
                                \addplot[soliddot,color=thirdcolor] coordinates {(6.5,1.1)} node[below left]{$(6.5,1.1)$};
                              \end{axis}
                          \end{tikzpicture}
                          
                      </latex-image>
                    </image>
                  </figure>
                </sidebyside>
                <!-- <p>
                  Before we go on, we should note that since the model is only valid above Timberline Lodge, we will only consider the graph between the <m>x</m>-values we found above, <m>[0,6.5]</m>, for the next part of the question.
                </p> -->
                  <!-- we can use <xref provisional="fact-absolute-value-equation-i">Fact</xref> to split apart the equation: -->
                  <!-- <md>
                    <mrow>x-3.25 \amp\approx 3.25 \amp \text{or} \amp\amp x-3.25 \amp\approx -3.25</mrow>
                    <mrow>x-3.25\addright{3.25} \amp\approx 3.226\addright{3.25} \amp \text{or} \amp\amp x-3.25\addright{3.25} \amp= -17158.7\addright{3.25}</mrow>
                    <mrow>x \amp\approx 6.5 \amp \text{or} \amp\amp x \amp\approx 0</mrow>
                  </md> -->
              </li>
              <li xml:id="ORCCA-t5NpWkIFnB" license="CC-BY-4.0">
                <p>
                  The inequality we are looking for will describe when the altitude is below <m>1.5</m> miles, but also above <m>1.1</m> miles based on the reality of the situation (since the model only works above Timberline lodge at <m>1.1</m> miles of altitude).
                  Since <m>f(x)</m> is the altitude,
                  the inequality we need is <m>1.1\le f(x)\lt 1.5</m>,
                  which becomes <m>1.1\le2.1-0.3077\cdot\abs{x-3.25}\lt 1.5</m>.
                  <!-- To solve this, -->
                  <!-- we need to input the formula and simplify before using one of the absolute value inequality rules. -->
                  <!-- <md>
                    <mrow>f(x)\amp\lt 1.5</mrow>
                    <mrow>2.1-0.3077\cdot\abs{x-3.25} \amp\lt 1.5</mrow>
                    <mrow>2.1-0.3077\cdot\abs{x-3.25}\subtractright{2.1} \amp\lt 1.5\subtractright{2.1}</mrow>
                    <mrow>-0.3077\cdot\abs{x-3.25} \amp\lt -0.6</mrow>
                    <mrow>\divideunder{-0.3077\cdot\abs{x-3.25}}{-0.3077} \amp\mathbin{\highlight{\gt}} \divideunder{-0.6}{-0.3077}</mrow>
                    <mrow>\abs{x-3.25} \amp\gt 1.95\amp\text{(note: this value is rounded)}</mrow>
                  </md>
                  At this point,
                  we can use <xref provisional="fact-absolute-value-inequalities-ii">Fact</xref>
                  to split apart the inequality:
                  <md>
                    <mrow>x-3.25 \amp\lt -1.95 \amp \text{or} \amp\amp x-3.25 \amp\gt 1.95</mrow>
                    <mrow>x \amp\lt 1.3 \amp \text{or} \amp\amp x \amp\gt 5.2</mrow>
                  </md> -->
                </p>
                <sidebyside widths="47% 47%" margins="0%">
                  <p>
                    Let's examine the graph again to solve this inequality:
                    We are looking for places on the graph where the <m>y</m>-value is above <m>1.1</m>, but also where the graph is below <m>1.5</m>. To find this, we will draw in lines at both of those <m>y</m>-values and find intersections with <m>f</m>.
                  </p>
                  <figure xml:id="ORCCA-O7oyRlNVtG" license="CC-BY-4.0">
                    <caption><m>y=f(x)</m>, the Graph of the Mt Hood Ascent and Descent</caption>
                    <image>
                      <shortdescription>a Cartesian graph with the graphs of f(x)=2.1-0.3077abs(x-3.25) and y=1.1 and y=1.5;the absolute value is an upside-down V which is highlighted above y=1.1 and below 1.5, with open circles where y=1.5</shortdescription>
                      <latex-image>
                           \begin{tikzpicture}
                              \begin{axis}[ xmin=-1, xmax=8, 
                                            ymin=-.5, ymax=3, 
                                            xtick={1,2,...,7}, 
                                            ytick={0.5,1,...,2.5},
                                            ]
                              \addplot+[firstcurve] coordinates {(-1,0.792) (3.25,2.1) (8,0.6385)} node[pos=0.3, sloped, above]{$y=f(x)$};
                              \addplot+[domain=-1:8] {1.1} node[below,pos=0.5] {$y=1.1$};
                              \addplot+[domain=-1:8] {1.5} node[above,pos=0.5] {$y=1.5$};
                              \addplot[highlightcurve,domain=0:1.3] coordinates {(0,1.1) (1.3,1.5)};
                              \addplot[highlightcurve,domain=5.2:6.5] coordinates {(5.2,1.5) (6.5,1.1)};
                              \addplot[hollowdot,draw=fourthcolor] coordinates {(1.3,1.5)} node[below right] {$(1.3,1.5)$};
                              \addplot[hollowdot,draw=fourthcolor] coordinates {(5.2,1.5)} node[above right] {$(5.2,1.5)$};
                              \addplot[soliddot,color=fourthcolor] coordinates {(0,1.1)} node[below right] {$(0,1.1)$};
                              \addplot[soliddot,color=fourthcolor] coordinates {(6.5,1.1)} node[below] {$(6.5,1.1)$};
                              \end{axis}
                          \end{tikzpicture}
                          
                      </latex-image>
                    </image>
                  </figure>
                </sidebyside>
                <p>
                    The highlighted portions of the graph have <m>x</m>-values that satisfy the inequalities <m>0\le x\lt1.3 \text{ or } 5.2\lt x\le 6.5</m>.
                  </p>
                 <p>
                  In conclusion,
                  based both on our math and the reality of the situation,
                  regions of the trail that are below <m>1.5</m> miles are those that are from Timberline Lodge
                  (at <m>0</m> miles on the trail),
                  to <m>1.3</m> miles along the trail and then also from <m>5.2</m> miles along the trail
                  (and by now we are on our way back down)
                  to <m>6.5</m> miles along the trail
                  (back at Timberline Lodge).
                  If we wanted to write this in interval notation,
                  we might write <m>[0,1.3)\cup(5.2,6.5]</m>.
                  There is a big portion along the trail
                  (from <m>1.3</m> miles to <m>5.2</m> miles)
                  that Phuong will be above the <m>1.5</m> mile altitude and should watch for signs of altitude sickness.
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </solution>
      </example>
  
  <!-- This subsection is over and above the CCOG. Sorry, Ross, you should frame this code. -->
  
  <!-- <subsection>
          <title>Solving Compound Inequalities Graphically</title>
          <p>So far we have focused on solving inequalities algebraically. Next, we will describe how to solve compound inequalities graphically. As an initial hint, if you are solving where line <m>1</m> is less or equal to line <m>2</m>, the first step is always to identify where (as in <m>x</m>-values) those two lines cross. After that, you need to decide if the inequality is true on the left or on the right of that intersection.</p>
          <example>
              <statement>
                  <p>Shown is a graph of <m>y=f(x)</m>, <m>y=g(x)</m>, and <m>y=h(x)</m>. Use the graph to solve the inequalities.</p>
                  <figure xml:id="figure-compound-inequality-example2">
                  <caption>Graphs of <m>y=f(x)</m>, <m>y=g(x)</m>, and <m>y=h(x)</m></caption>
                      <image>
                          <shortdescription>A Cartesian graph of three thick lines, y=f(x), y=g(x), and y=h(x) whose formulas are unknown. f passes through (0,4) and (4,0). g passes through (0,-2) and (4,0). h passes through (0,1) and (1,3). Each line extends to the edge of the grid with arrows at both ends.</shortdescription>
                          <latex-image>
                              <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                                  \begin{axis}[axis x line=middle,axis y line=middle, xlabel={$x$},ylabel={$y$}, xmin=-4,xmax=7,ymin=-6,ymax=6, xtick={-3,-2,...,6}, ytick={-5,-4,...,5}, grid=both, axis line style={{Kite}-{Kite},very thick}]
                                  \addplot[firstcurve, domain=-2:7] {4-x} node[below left, sloped, pos=1]{$y=f(x)$};
                                  \addplot[secondcurve, domain=-4:7] {(1/2)*x-2} node[above left, sloped, pos=1]{$y=g(x)$};
                                  \addplot[thirdcurve, domain=-3.5:2.5] {2*x+1} node[below, sloped, pos=0.9]{$y=h(x)$};
                                  \end{axis}
                              \end{tikzpicture}
                              ]]>
                          </latex-image>
                      </image>
                  </figure>
                  <p><ol marker="a.">
                      <li><p>Solve the inequality <m>g(x)\geq f(x)</m> graphically.</p></li>
                      <li><p>Solve the inequality <m>h(x)\lt f(x)</m> or <m>g(x)\geq 0</m> graphically.</p></li>
                      <li><p>Solve the inequality <m>h(x)\gt 5</m> and <m>f(x)\geq-1</m> graphically.</p></li>
                      <li><p>Solve the inequality <m>f(x)\lt g(x) \le h(x)</m> graphically.</p></li>
                  </ol></p>
              </statement>
              <solution>
                  <p>To solve the inequalities, we must look for the <m>x</m>-values where the inequalities are true.<ol marker="a.">
                      <li>
                           <sidebyside widths="47% 47%" margins="0%" valign="middle">
                              <p>The inequality <m>g(x)\geq f(x)</m> tells us that we need to look for <m>x</m>-values where the <m>y</m>-values of <m>g</m> are above (or equal) to the values of <m>f</m>: in short, where is <m>g</m> above <m>f</m>? First look for where those lines cross. Once we see that <m>g</m> crosses <m>f</m> at <m>x=4</m>, we need to decide if <m>g</m> is above <m>f</m> on the left or right of that crossing. It appears that <m>g</m> is above <m>f</m> on the right. We will highlight the regions along <m>f</m> and <m>g</m> that satisfy the inequality. Now we have to identify the <m>x</m>-values that describe the highlighted region. In this case, they are <m>[4,\infty)</m>, which is our solution set.</p>
                              <figure xml:id="figure-compound-inequality-example-solution-1">
                              <caption>Graphs of <m>y=f(x)</m> and <m>y=g(x)</m> with where <m>g(x)\geq f(x)</m> is highlighted</caption>
                                  <image>
                                      <shortdescription>A Cartesian graph of two thick lines, y=f(x) and y=g(x) whose formulas are unknown. f passes through (0,4) and (4,0). g passes through (0,-2) and (4,0). Note that the lines intersect at (4,0) and a solid dot is at this point. Each line extends to the edge of the grid with arrows at both ends. The potions of both lines that are to the right of x=4 are highlighted extra thick.</shortdescription>
                                      <latex-image>
                                          <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                                              \begin{axis}[axis x line=middle,axis y line=middle, xlabel={$x$},ylabel={$y$}, xmin=-4,xmax=7,ymin=-6,ymax=6, xtick={-3,-2,...,6}, ytick={-5,-4,...,5}, grid=both, axis line style={{Kite}-{Kite},very thick}]
                                              \addplot[firstcurve, domain=-2:7] {4-x} node[above, sloped, pos=0.45]{$y=f(x)$};
                                              \addplot[secondcurve, domain=-4:7] {(1/2)*x-2} node[above, pos=0.15, sloped]{$y=g(x)$};
                                              \addplot[-{Kite}, very thick, color=fourthcolor, domain=4:7] {4-x};
                                              \addplot[-{Kite}, very thick, color=fourthcolor, domain=4:7] {(1/2)*x-2};
                                              \addplot[only marks, color=fourthcolor] (4,0);
                                              \end{axis}
                                          \end{tikzpicture}
                                          ]]>
                                      </latex-image>
                                  </image>
                              </figure>
                          </sidebyside>
                      </li>
                      <li><p>To solve the compound inequality <m>h(x)\lt f(x)</m> or <m>g(x)\le 0</m> we need to
                              <ul>
                                  <li>look for <m>x</m>-values where <m>h</m> is below <m>f</m></li>
                                  <li>look for <m>x</m>-values where <m>g</m> is above (or equal to) the <m>y</m>-value <m>0</m>.</li>
                              </ul></p>
                              <p>Since this is an <q>or</q> statement, if <em>either</em> of the items are satisfied, those values are solutions of the compound inequality.</p>
                          <sidebyside widths="47% 47%" margins="0%">
                              <p>First, let's look for <m>x</m>-values where <m>h</m> is below <m>f</m>. To answer this, we will highlight the regions along <m>h</m> and <m>f</m> that satisfy the inequality. Now we have to identify the <m>x</m>-values that describe the highlighted region. Note that we shouldn't include the point of intersection of the lines since <m>h(x)\nless f(x)</m> at <m>x=1</m>. In this case, the solution set is <m>(-\infty,1)</m>.</p>
                              <figure xml:id="figure-compound-inequality-example-solution-2a">
                              <caption>Graphs of <m>y=f(x)</m> and <m>y=h(x)</m> with where <m>h(x)\lt f(x)</m> is highlighted</caption>
                                  <image>
                                      <shortdescription>A Cartesian graph of two thick lines, y=f(x) and y=h(x) whose formulas are unknown. f passes through (0,4) and (4,0). h passes through (0,1) and (1,3). Each line extends to the edge of the grid with arrows at both ends. The two lines intersect at (1,3) with an open circle. The portions of both graphs that are to the left of x=1 are highlighted extra thick.</shortdescription>
                                      <latex-image>
                                          <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                                              \begin{axis}[axis x line=middle,axis y line=middle, xlabel={$x$},ylabel={$y$},  xmin=-4,xmax=7,ymin=-6,ymax=6, xtick={-3,-2,...,6}, ytick={-5,-4,...,5}, grid=both, axis line style={{Kite}-{Kite},very thick}]
                                              \addplot[firstcurve, domain=-2:7] {4-x} node[below left, sloped, pos=1]{$y=f(x)$};
                                              \addplot[thirdcurve, domain=-3.5:2.5] {2*x+1} node[below right, sloped, pos=0.75]{$y=h(x)$};
                                              \addplot[{Kite}-, very thick, color=fourthcolor, domain=-2:1] {4-x};
                                              \addplot[{Kite}-, very thick, color=fourthcolor, domain=-3.5:1] {2*x+1};
                                              \addplot[hollowdot, only marks, color=fourthcolor] (1,3);
                                              \end{axis}
                                          \end{tikzpicture}
                                          ]]>
                                      </latex-image>
                                  </image>
                              </figure>
                          </sidebyside>
                          <sidebyside widths="47% 47%" margins="0%">
                              <p>Next, let's look for <m>x</m>-values where <m>g</m> is above (or equal to) the <m>y</m>-value <m>0</m>. To answer this, we will highlight the regions along <m>g</m> and <m>y=0</m> that satisfy the inequality. Now we have to identify the <m>x</m>-values that describe the highlighted region. Note that we should include the point of intersection since the inequality has an <q>equal to</q> in it. In this case, the solution set is <m>[4,\infty)</m>.</p>
                              <figure xml:id="figure-compound-inequality-example-solution-2b">
                              <caption>Graphs of <m>y=g(x)</m> and <m>y=0</m> with where <m>g(x)\geq 0</m> is highlighted</caption>
                                  <image>
                                      <shortdescription>A Cartesian graph of two thick lines, y=g(x) (whose formula is unknown) and y=0 . g passes through (0,-2) and (4,0). Each line extends to the edge of the grid with arrows at both ends. The two lines intersect at (4,0) with an solid dot. The portions of both graphs that are to the right of x=0 are highlighted extra thick.</shortdescription>
                                      <latex-image>
                                          <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                                              \begin{axis}[axis x line=middle,axis y line=middle, xlabel={$x$},ylabel={$y$},  xmin=-4,xmax=7,ymin=-6,ymax=6, xtick={-3,-2,...,6}, ytick={-5,-4,...,5}, grid=both, axis line style={{Kite}-{Kite},very thick}]
                                              \addplot[secondcurve, domain=-4:7] {(1/2)*x-2} node[below, pos=0.12, sloped]{$y=g(x)$};
                                              \addplot[fifthcurve, domain=-4:7] {0.05} node[above, pos=0.12]{$y=0$};
                                              \addplot[-{Kite}, very thick, color=fourthcolor, domain=4:7] {(1/2)*x-2};
                                              \addplot[-{Kite}, very thick, color=fourthcolor, domain=4:7] {0};
                                              \addplot[only marks, color=fourthcolor] (4,0);
                                              \end{axis}
                                          \end{tikzpicture}
                                          ]]>
                                      </latex-image>
                                  </image>
                              </figure>
                          </sidebyside>
                          <p>Recall that the compound inequality that we are solving is <m>h(x)\lt f(x)</m> or <m>g(x)\le 0</m>. Since this is an <q>or</q> statement we need to take the union of the separate solution sets. Thus, the full solution set is <m>(-\infty,1)\cup[4,\infty)</m>. Note that this cannot be simplified because the regions don't overlap.</p>
                      </li>
                      <li><p>As in the previous example, <m>h(x)\gt 5</m> and <m>f(x)\geq-1</m> asks us to do two things.<ul>
                              <li>Find <m>x</m>-values where <m>h</m> is above the <m>y</m>-value <m>5</m>, and</li>
                              <li>Find <m>x</m>-values where <m>f</m> is above (or equal) the <m>y</m>-value <m>-1</m>.</li>
                          </ul>Since this is an <q>and</q> statement, in the end we need <m>x</m>-values where <em>both</em> of the items to be satisfied, and those values are solutions of the compound inequality.</p>
                          <sidebyside widths="47% 47%" margins="0%">
                              <p>We will first highlight the regions along <m>h</m> and <m>y=5</m> that satisfy the inequality. Now we have to identify the <m>x</m>-values that describe the highlighted region. Note that we shouldn't include the point of intersection due to the strict inequality. In this case, the solution set is <m>(2,\infty)</m>.</p>
                              <figure xml:id="figure-compound-inequality-example-solution-3a">
                              <caption>Graphs of <m>y=h(x)</m> and <m>y=5</m> with where <m>h(x)\gt 5</m> is highlighted</caption>
                                  <image>
                                      <shortdescription></shortdescription>
                                      <latex-image>
                                          <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                                              \begin{axis}[axis x line=middle,axis y line=middle, xlabel={$x$},ylabel={$y$}, xmin=-4,xmax=7,ymin=-6,ymax=6, xtick={-3,-2,...,6}, ytick={-5,-4,...,5}, grid=both, axis line style={{Kite}-{Kite},very thick}]
                                              \addplot[fifthcurve, domain=-4:7] {5} node[pos=0.1, below]{$y=5$};
                                              \addplot[thirdcurve, domain=-3.5:2.5] {2*x+1} node[pos=0.05, above right, sloped]{$y=h(x)$};
                                              \addplot[-{Kite}, very thick, color=fourthcolor, domain=2:2.5] {2*x+1};
                                              \addplot[-{Kite}, very thick, color=fourthcolor, domain=2:7] {5};
                                              \addplot[hollowdot, only marks, color=fourthcolor] (2,5);
                                              \end{axis}
                                          \end{tikzpicture}
                                          ]]>
                                      </latex-image>
                                  </image>
                              </figure>
                          </sidebyside>
                          <sidebyside widths="47% 47%" margins="0%">
                              <p>We will next highlight the regions along <m>f</m> and <m>y=-1</m> that satisfy the inequality. Now we have to identify the <m>x</m>-values that describe the highlighted region. Note that we should include the point of intersection. In this case, the solution set is <m>(-\infty,5]</m>.</p>
                              <figure xml:id="figure-compound-inequality-example-solution-3b">
                              <caption>Graphs of <m>y=f(x)</m> and <m>y=-1</m> with where <m>f(x)\geq-1</m> is highlighted</caption>
                                  <image>
                                      <shortdescription></shortdescription>
                                      <latex-image>
                                          <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                                              \begin{axis}[axis x line=middle,axis y line=middle, xlabel={$x$},ylabel={$y$},  xmin=-4,xmax=7,ymin=-6,ymax=6, xtick={-3,-2,...,6}, ytick={-5,-4,...,5}, grid=both, axis line style={{Kite}-{Kite},very thick}]
                                              \addplot[fifthcurve, domain=-4:7] {-1} node[below, pos=0.15]{$y=-1$};
                                              \addplot[firstcurve, domain=-2:7] {4-x} node[above, pos=0.45, sloped]{$y=f(x)$};
                                              \addplot[{Kite}-, very thick, color=fourthcolor, domain=-2:5] {4-x};
                                              \addplot[{Kite}-, very thick, color=fourthcolor, domain=-4:5] {-1};
                                              \addplot[only marks, color=fourthcolor] (5,-1);
                                              \end{axis}
                                          \end{tikzpicture}
                                          ]]>
                                      </latex-image>
                                  </image>
                              </figure>
                          </sidebyside>
                          <p>Recall that the compound inequality that we are solving is <m>h(x)\gt 5</m> and <m>f(x)\geq-1</m>. Since this is an <q>and</q> statement we need to take the intersection of the separate solution sets. Thus, the full solution set is <m>(-\infty,5]\cap(2,\infty)=(2,5]</m>.</p>
                      </li>
                      <li><p>The inequality <m>f(x)\lt g(x) \le h(x)</m> is a triple inequality. The best way to solve these graphically is to recall <xref ref="remark-triple-inequality">Remark</xref>. This remark would say that <m>f(x)\lt g(x) \le h(x)</m> can be broken into the compound inequality <m>f(x)\lt g(x)</m> and <m>g(x) \le h(x)</m>. Now the problem looks similar to one we have already done. Since this is an <q>and</q> statement, in the end we need <m>x</m>-values where <em>both</em> of the items to be satisfied, and those values are solutions of the compound inequality.</p>
                          <sidebyside widths="47% 47%" margins="0%">
                              <p>We will first highlight the regions along <m>f</m> and <m>g</m> that satisfy the inequality. Now we have to identify the <m>x</m>-values that describe the highlighted region. Note that we shouldn't include the point of intersection due to the strict inequality. In this case, the solution set is <m>(4,\infty)</m>.</p>
                              <figure xml:id="figure-compound-inequality-example-solution-4a">
                              <caption>Graphs of <m>y=f(x)</m> and <m>y=g(x)</m> with where <m>f(x)\lt g(x)</m> is highlighted</caption>
                                  <image>
                                      <shortdescription></shortdescription>
                                      <latex-image>
                                          <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                                              \begin{axis}[axis x line=middle,axis y line=middle, xlabel={$x$},ylabel={$y$}, xmin=-4,xmax=7,ymin=-6,ymax=6, xtick={-3,-2,...,6}, ytick={-5,-4,...,5}, grid=both, axis line style={{Kite}-{Kite},very thick}]
                                              \addplot[firstcurve, domain=-2:7] {4-x} node[above, sloped, pos=0.45]{$y=f(x)$};
                                              \addplot[secondcurve, domain=-4:7] {(1/2)*x-2} node[above right, sloped, pos=0.05]{$y=g(x)$};
                                              \addplot[-{Kite}, very thick, color=fourthcolor, domain=4:7] {4-x};
                                              \addplot[-{Kite}, very thick, color=fourthcolor, domain=4:7] {(1/2)*x-2};
                                              \addplot[hollowdot, only marks, color=fourthcolor] (4,0);
                                              \end{axis}
                                          \end{tikzpicture}
                                          ]]>
                                      </latex-image>
                                  </image>
                              </figure>
                          </sidebyside>
                          <sidebyside widths="47% 47%" margins="0%">
                              <p>We will next highlight the regions along <m>g</m> and <m>h</m> that satisfy the inequality. Now we have to identify the <m>x</m>-values that describe the highlighted region. Note that we should include the point of intersection. In this case, the solution set is <m>[-2,\infty)</m>.</p>
                              <figure xml:id="figure-compound-inequality-example-solution-4b">
                              <caption>Graphs of <m>y=g(x)</m> and <m>y=h(x)</m> with where <m>g(x) \le h(x)</m> is highlighted</caption>
                                  <image>
                                      <shortdescription></shortdescription>
                                      <latex-image>
                                          <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                                              \begin{axis}[axis x line=middle,axis y line=middle, xlabel={$x$},ylabel={$y$},  xmin=-4,xmax=7,ymin=-6,ymax=6, xtick={-3,-2,...,6}, ytick={-5,-4,...,5}, grid=both, axis line style={{Kite}-{Kite},very thick}]
                                              \addplot[secondcurve, domain=-4:7] {(1/2)*x-2} node[above left, sloped, pos=1]{$y=g(x)$};
                                              \addplot[thirdcurve, domain=-3.5:2.5] {2*x+1} node[below, sloped, pos=0.9]{$y=h(x)$};
                                              \addplot[-{Kite}, very thick, color=fourthcolor, domain=-2:7] {(1/2)*x-2};
                                              \addplot[-{Kite}, very thick, color=fourthcolor, domain=-2:2.5] {2*x+1};
                                              \addplot[only marks, color=fourthcolor] (-2,-3);
                                              \end{axis}
                                          \end{tikzpicture}
                                          ]]>
                                      </latex-image>
                                  </image>
                              </figure>
                          </sidebyside>
                          <p>Recall that the compound inequality that we are solving is <m>f(x)\lt g(x)</m> and <m>g(x) \le h(x)</m>. Since this is an <q>and</q> statement we need to take the intersection of the separate solution sets. Thus, the full solution set is <m>[-2,\infty)\cap(4,\infty)=(4,\infty)</m>.</p>
                      </li>
                  </ol></p>
              </solution>
          </example>
      </subsection> -->
  
  <reading-questions>
      <!-- <exercise>
